node.text:
“The beauty in us reclaiming Juneteenth is that we can define and decide how we want to celebrate it.” 

In anticipation of Juneteenth, celebrated June 19th, join Googlers Zora, Samantha, and Kwame as they share their Juneteenth journeys and demonstrate the interconnectivity between history, legacy, and how it’s shaped their journey to the present day.

Head to the #linkinbio for the full video on our YouTube page.

node.text: The possibilities of 2021 are everywhere, and we’re making sure you have the tools you need to hit the ground running. Head to goo.gle/careers to browse helpful tools and open positions at Google and make 2021 a year filled with “new.”

node.text:
In honor of #VeteransDay, we’re sharing the stories of veterans across Google. First up, hear how Googler Yaser Chow’s (@yaserchow) unique experience as a Marine has translated into valuable skills as a Senior Financial Analyst.⁣
⁣
Head to https://goo.gle/3prQ57x for more Googler veteran stories, and for some tips on resumes, mentorships, and interviewing at Google for veterans and military spouses. #lifeatgoogle

node.title: Yaser Chow: US Marine Veteran and Senior Financial Analyst at Google

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Life at Google on September 07, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
This month marks the 20th anniversary of our first overseas office — in Tokyo. To celebrate, we’re reflecting on some of the moments and themes that have defined Google’s 20 years in Asia, from the birth of Google Maps in Sydney to the opening of our first data centers in Singapore and Taiwan, and more. 

Scroll through ➡️ for a preview trip down memory lane and tap the bio link for the full scoop on the Keyword blog!

🤖: the scene at Google’s data center in Singapore when it opened in 2013
🐤: Sundar Pichai meets “Flappy Bird” creator Dong Nguyen in Hanoi in 2015
🎉: Welcoming new HTC colleagues to Google’s engineering workforce in Taiwan in 2018
🗺️: Filming for Street View at Uluṟu-Kata Tjuṯa National Park in Central Australia in accordance with Tjukurpa law

#lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC

node.text:
“As a physicist I am a problem solver and a life long learner by heart. Being able to combine both passions makes the job meaningful and very exciting for me.”

We caught up with Dr. Diana Nanova, a Google Cloud Customer Engineer based in Berlin, Germany:

How would you describe your job?
You can imagine Google Cloud services just like lego bricks — they all come in a different shape and size and serve a different purpose. Some of the lego bricks are good to build a foundation (IT infrastructure), some of them help you build roads (networking), store data, analyze data, do machine learning on data etc. My job is to advise our customers which lego bricks to use and how to use them to solve their individual challenges. And if we are missing a lego brick with a particular feature, I work with our product teams, so that no problem remains unsolved for our customers.

What makes you excited to log in every day?
As a Customer Engineer you work with cutting edge cloud technology, which helps our customers to solve problems and do things that weren't possible before, especially when pushing the boundaries of artificial intelligence and machine learning.

Interested in joining Diana in the customer engineer space? Explore open roles at the #linkinbio

node.accessibility_caption: Andrew sits at his desk at home. On his desk is a Noogler hat, a screen with the Chrome logo on it, a keyboard and a laptop.

node.text:
“I’ve had a somewhat unusual path compared to most folks in my position. My career background is largely in tech startups. I live in Nairobi, which has a thriving community of creative talent from which I’ve benefited from and to which I’ve contributed. My time as an entrepreneur working on financial technology exposed me to opportunities that helped diversify my experiences and build up the empathy and skill set that is extremely invaluable as a product manager.”

Head to the link in bio for the latest #MyPathToGoogle, where Andrew Kamau from our Nairobi office shares how his career took him from startups in Kenya to creating products at Google." #lifeatgoogle

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Life at Google on August 30, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
“In my early career I tried out a lot of different things in tech. I've done software engineering, research, product management and business development. This kind of exposure and curiosity enabled me to grow from being a pure techie to developing an understanding of the business side of things. These functions don't work in isolation, one has to have the understanding of how they fit and work together. Merging these worlds has been incredibly important for opening doors in my career.”

Bangalore-based Amruta Joshi, Director for Cloud Engineering Delivery, shares how her depth of experience guides her leadership style.

“As a leader within @GoogleCloud, I appreciate all the different roles, skills and perspectives that people bring. I value each individual and their contribution. I make sure I understand and support their professional development and their daily responsibilities. It’s important to let them shine and celebrate their wins. And it’s important they feel connected to Google’s purpose and mission. If I can do all those things, then that’s what makes Google Cloud an environment where everyone feels included and inspired.”

Tap the link in bio to check out engineering roles on the Google Cloud team around the world. #lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC

node.accessibility_caption: Tara stands in a hallway leaning against a yellow pillar. In the background are more colorful pillars and the glass side of an office building.

node.text:
“Some work GAIN (Google’s Aboriginal and Indigenous Network) has done that we're proudest of involves creating and launching initiatives in areas like hiring, recruiting, retention, wellness, cultural events and internet connectivity in Indigenous communities. We work to shed light on the Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls campaigns , support Indigenous small businesses, and promote racial equity and justice initiatives. GAIN has also helped highlight educational tools such as training with ComIT, online STEM programming and #GrowWithGoogle , which worked with elementary school students in their local library and makerspace in Iqaluit.”

Head to the Keyword blog (link in bio) to meet Tara Rush from our office in Kitchener, Canada. One of the five people who lead GAIN, Tara shares how this employee-run group gives Indigenous Googlers a safe place to nurture their communities. #lifeatgoogle

node.accessibility_caption: Madhumita sits at her desk at home.

node.text:
We’re counting down the days until Decode with Google India (26th August, 2021!), a virtual event for tech-makers, entrepreneurs, and academia to get a sneak peek at some of the toughest and most interesting challenges that Googlers in India are solving for. Registration is open now, head to the #linkinbio to sign up.

To give you a sneak peek at just one topic covered at Decode with Google, we chatted with Madhumita from Google’s Bangalore office. Madhumita's team, WorkSpace Security Center, builds a security platform to provide customer security insights and to help customers to diagnose and mitigate security issues in the Workspace. She discussed and what it was like to join Google remotely:

“I joined Google amidst of COVID pandemic and a nationwide lockdown in India. Till today, I haven’t been able to visit the Google Bangalore office or meet my colleagues. However, in this difficult time, Google’s smooth remote onboarding process made my life much easier. 

My teammates are extremely supportive and always available to answer my random queries about different processes inside Google. It’s a pleasure to be part of such a thriving team that is tirelessly working to keep customers' workspace safe and secure. Security is one of the major concerns of decision-makers as they make their purchasing decisions to move to the cloud.” 

#lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC

node.accessibility_caption: Dina sitting inside a large Google Cloud sculpture.

node.text:
"Always keep in mind that a career path does not have to be linear. Each person has their own path to take that may have twists and turns. The key is to stick with it and keep searching for the path that sparks passion within you."

In today's #MyPathToGoogle meet Dina Amin, Head Of Cloud Marketing for the Middle East,Turkey and Africa whose path to Google involves 15 countries, over five different career fields, and one serendipitous business school event. #linkinbio

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Life at Google on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 4 people, people standing and outdoors.

node.text: "I was supposed to go back to India and get married. I wasn’t going to pursue computer science.” In the Google blog engineering director, Bhavna Chhabra, shares her story and three specific lessons she learned along the way. #linkinbio

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Life at Google on August 11, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, screen, indoor and text that says 'Google for Educat Brona Google for Education O'.

node.text:
“The best part of my job is seeing the folks on my team grow into their potential. I’m really focused on coaching and sharing what I can. One thing I’m very deliberately trying to do in my team is offer people leadership experience. I try to carve out roles and initiatives that allow them to learn and hopefully use that learning to progress through to becoming a manager (but only if it still appeals to them - it may not!). Another area is mentoring. As manager it's my job to help find those programs within Google Cloud and find mentors for folks on my team who would benefit from them.  It’s great to see people succeed, whether it’s a promotion, a new role, a major learning moment or just simply solving a major customer's problem and knowing they have had a positive impact.“
 
We chatted with Sydney-based Stephen Davern, who leads our Customer Engineering team focused on small and medium businesses, about how he thinks about hiring and progression on his teams.

“Essentially a Customer Engineer makes the impossible possible! Working in Google Cloud is all about taking amazing technology and putting it into the hands of some of the coolest up-and-coming startups in the world, helping them accomplish things they never even thought were possible. 

When hiring I look for people who are curious about technology, how it fits together, and enjoy problem solving. And I look for people who have a desire to make a difference and to go that extra mile for customers and their teammates.”

Tap the #linkinbio to explore Customer Engineer roles with the Google Cloud team. #lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC

node.accessibility_caption: Akash stands in front of a Google building with a multicolor Google logo across the top. In the background is landscaping and a fence.

node.text:
“Believe in yourself, especially during tough times and failures. Anyone out there reading this, just get past the fear of failure and start learning from it. Failures teach us much more than success.”

In the latest #MyPathToGoogle, meet Akash Mukherjee (@akashmuk), a Security Engineer at our Mountain View office, who shares what makes his work challenging and exciting, as well as a few tips he’s picked up along the way. Tap the #linkinbio for his story and advice. #lifeatgoogle

buttons.text: Visit the COVID-19 Information Center for vaccine resources.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Life at Google on August 04, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, sitting and indoor.

node.text:
“Remote onboarding can be hard, but my fellow Googlers made the journey super smooth. I had heard about the culture at Google, how helpful people were and how exhilarating  the office spaces were. I haven't been to the office yet, but I have experienced how genuinely helpful, friendly and smart my fellow Googlers are.”

We chatted with Anupama Dutt, a Senior Program Manager on the Google Maps team at our Hyderabad office, about her role leading a team that helps keep Maps up to date with accurate, real world information, and what it was like to join Google while working remotely.

“It’s a product that is very close to my heart. It has helped me be an independent explorer, it has kept me safe from getting lost :). I don’t know how I could have explored so many places in so many countries without Google Maps.

I lead the trust efforts to keep Maps safe from harmful content through a combination of machine and human intelligence. It gives me a sense of gratitude that my team and I have had the opportunity to deliver several critical features to help Google map users, businesses, patients seeking hospitals, people looking for vaccines centers and so forth during these challenging times. The fact that we are in our little ways able to help organize information on the Map and make sure it’s useful and abuse free, keeps me going.”

Thanks, Anupama! Tap the #linkinbio to explore open roles on the Google Maps team in Hyderabad and around the world. #lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC

node.text:
New Zealand Googlers are moving into our brand new Auckland office this week! We’re also establishing a new local engineering team and launching additional cloud infrastructure. Learn more and take a peek inside the new space. Scroll through for a few highlights, including:

🛶 A kayak-themed reception desk.
🖼️ The largest digital ceiling in New Zealand.
🌊 A coastal-inspired event space overlooking the Auckland harbour where we’ll host business leaders, technologists and the wider community.

#lifeatgoogle #lifeatgoogleAPAC
